Air Pollutant Transport Along Lake Michigan

Benjamin Dorava, Sanjay Murali, Akshat Jain

Introduction

Air pollution has detrimental impacts on community health, especially for vulnerable populations. Some of these impacts can be mitigated by issuing air quality advisories, which are informed by predictions of atmospheric flow.

We are interested in analyzing air quality monitoring data from a fixed location 40 miles north of downtown Chicago, and seek to investigate possible correlations between wind velocity and ozone concentrations.

From our analysis comparing mean ozone concentrations between samples of similar wind velocity, we find that there is a positive correlation between north-westward blowing wind and ozone concentration.

Background

One source of air pollutantssuch as ozone and its precursorsis automobiles. The increased concentration of automobiles within cities predictably means that ozone concentrations are typically greater than in rural areas. This investigation is interested in the effects of wind as it transports ozone from urban towards rural areas.

The Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources maintains several air quality monitoring sites across the state. The data set we analyze consists of two consecutive years of seasonally reported ozone concentrations and meteorological conditions measured by the Chiwaukee Prairie Stateline station (AQS: 55-059-0019).

This station records hourly ozone concentrations during March through October, and data was available for 20212022.1 The station is located less than 1,000 feet from the shore of Lake Michigan in Pleasant Prairie, Kenosha, which is roughly 40 miles north of Chicago.2

We are interested in 3 variables: zonal and meridional components of flow, and ozone concentration. The zonal (meridional) component of flow, conventionally written as \(u\) (\(v\)) refers to the magnitude of the wind vector in the \(\hat{i}\) (\(\hat{j}\)) direction; in other words, the portion of the wind blowing purely in the direction of west-to-east (south-to-north). These components of flow are determined trigonometrically from the reported wind speed and direction, and are in units of \({ms}^{-1}\). Ozone concentration is reported in units of parts per billion (\(ppb\)).

Analysis

The first graphical summary of the data was simply of ozone concentrations plotted against components of wind velocity. Because the points are plotted against the velocity vector, each point can be thought of as the head of the wind vector, whose tail is the origin.

In order to determine local statistics across the continuous data set, values were binned by rounding to the nearest whole \({ms}^{-1}\).

Bins with fewer than 30 members are not included, while outliers remain visible.

We have included annotations for the five regions we will compare:

  • Gold: Calm wind, slightly skewed Eastward to account for prevailing wind
  • Top-Left: North-westward wind
  • Top-Right: North-eastward wind
  • Bottom-Left: South-westward wind
  • Bottom-Right: South-eastward wind

Perhaps most apparently, the region of calm wind has the lowest mean ozone concentration. This would suggest that at this site, ozone concentration is positively correlated with wind speed.

The Top-Left region appears to have a highest mean concentration. This would suggest that at this site, ozone concentration is positively correlated with wind blowing towards the north-west.

Discussion

##TODO: Continue analysis into discussion, broader interpretation of analysis, summary of conclusions

Below is an example of lake breeze from this data set, characterized by drop in land temperature, shifting wind direction, increased ozone levels.

These lake breeze events are sporadic, which means that the wind may blow north-west even in the absence of a lake breeze. In these cases, considerably lower values of ozone concentration would be recorded than during lake breeze events. This is to say that if these increased levels of ozone are caused by lake breeze events, we would expect a notable variance between ozone concentrations. This is supported when we plot standard deviation against components of the wind vector.

As predicted, we see a larger standard deviation in the ozone concentrations carried by north-westward winds.

Further research could include an investigation into the meteorological conditions preceding a lake-breeze event, such as difference in air temperature above land and above water.
